geology_info.concentration_process: The Suite Of Igneous And Volcanic Rocks Comprising The Bushveld Igneous Complex Is Believed To Have Derived From A Common Magma. Selective Differentiation Followed, From Ultrabasics To Acid Rocks With (Selective) Concentrations Of Ore Minerals And Metals.
geology_info.ore_control: The Various Components Of The Bushveld Igneous Complex Have Been Emplaced In Successive Eruptions As Sheet-Like Masses Into The Pretoria Series Volcanics (Transvaal System), And In Some Cases Into One Another, Dipping Inward Toward The Center Giving A Cone-Like Structure To The Complex As A Whole.
geology_info.structure: Inward-Dipping Cone-Like Structure; Folding And Faulting (Including Low-Angle Thrusting) Exists, But Are Of Minor Importance; Erosion, Peneplanation And Build-Up Of Younger Sediments Are Basic Criteria Regionally., The Area'S Upper, Middle And Lower Chrome Groups (Underlying The Merensky Reef) Are Extraordinarily Uniform As To Composition And Thickness.  Faults And Folds, Locally, Are Of Minor Importance Only.  Seam Undulations, However, Are Common And Thus Present Localized (Albeit Moderate) Changes In The Dip.
The Deposits Are Cut Off At The Great Huntsville Fault
